Communicated by:
ProMED-SoAs
<promed-SoAs@promedmail.org>

[Dengue is a major public health problem in India. It is transmitted by the bite of the vector, the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, infected with one of the 4 dengue virus serotypes. It is endemic throughout India, mostly in the metropolitan cities and towns (http://www.nvbdcp.gov.in/dengue5.html).

As per the media report above, 217 confirmed dengue cases with 4 deaths were reported in Dakshina Kannada district of Karnataka in June 2015, whereas in June 2014, 63 positive cases and 2 deaths were reported in the district. To prevent further spread of the disease, mosquito source reduction and community awareness regarding prevention and control of dengue are needed.

In 2014, Karnataka reported 3358 dengue cases including 2 deaths (http://www.nvbdcp.gov.in/den-cd.html).

The National Vector Borne Disease Control Programme in India recommends the following preventive measures against dengue: removing water from coolers and other small containers at least once a week; using aerosol repellent during the daytime to prevent the bites of mosquitoes; avoiding clothes that expose arms and legs; not allowing children to play in shorts and half-sleeved clothes; and using mosquito nets or mosquito repellents while sleeping during the daytime, since the mosquito is a daytime biter (http://www.nvbdcp.gov.in/dengue12.html).

Preventing or reducing dengue virus transmission depends entirely on controlling the mosquito vectors or interruption of human-vector contact (http://www.who.int/denguecontrol/control_strategies/en/).

Maps of India can be seen at http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/india/india-political-map.htm and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3487514,888. Dakshina Kannada is a coastal district in the state of Karnataka in India. Sheltered by the Western Ghats on the east and surrounded by the Arabian Sea on the west, Dakshina Kannada receives abundant rainfall during the monsoon https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dakshina_Kannada. - Mod.GS]
